The `people` array returned from your database is returning the people list with the first value as `empty`, so when you try to access `this.state.people[0]`, it won&#39;t find anything there and it will throw the error.

[![enter image description here][1]][1]

There seems to be a discussion [here][2] as to why Firebase collections seem to begin with a null row.


  [1]: https://i.stack.imgur.com/KdRO7.png
  [2]: https://stackoverflow.com/questions/15534917/why-do-firebase-collections-seem-to-begin-with-a-null-row

However, you can make a change in your `firebasePeopleListener` in `App.js` and filter out the response to only add to the state people that have an `id` set.

    firebasePeopleListener = () =&gt; {
            database().ref(&#39;people/&#39;).on(&#39;value&#39;, (snapshot) =&gt; {
                let people = snapshot.val();
                let updatedPeople = [];
    
                for(let i in people) {
                    if(people.hasOwnProperty(i) &amp;&amp; people[i].id) {
                        updatedPeople.push(people[i]);
                    }
                }
                this.setState({
                    people: updatedPeople
                });
            });
        };

This should fix your problem for now.

